events.description: After a night of negotiation, Claudius is accepted as Roman emperor by the Senate.
events.html: • 41 – After a night of negotiation, Claudius is accepted as Roman emperor by the Senate.[1]

events.description: In the Battle of the Zab, the Abbasid rebels defeat the Umayyad Caliphate, leading to the overthrow of the dynasty.
events.html: • 750 – In the Battle of the Zab, the Abbasid rebels defeat the Umayyad Caliphate, leading to the overthrow of the dynasty.[2]

events.description: Fourteen-year-old Edward III ascends the throne of England after his father the king is forced to abdicate by Queen Isabella and her lover, Roger Mortimer.
events.html: • 1327 – Fourteen-year-old Edward III ascends the throne of England after his father the king is forced to abdicate by Queen Isabella and her lover, Roger Mortimer.[3]

events.description: A strong earthquake strikes the South Alpine region of Friuli in modern Italy, causing considerable damage to buildings as far away as Rome.
events.html: • 1348 – A strong earthquake strikes the South Alpine region of Friuli in modern Italy, causing considerable damage to buildings as far away as Rome.[4]

events.description: The Treaty of Constantinople ends the 16-year-long First Ottoman–Venetian War.
events.html: • 1479 – The Treaty of Constantinople ends the 16-year-long First Ottoman–Venetian War.[5]

events.description: Alfonso II becomes King of Naples.
events.html: • 1494 – Alfonso II becomes King of Naples.[6]

events.description: Coronation of Francis I of France takes place at Reims Cathedral, where the new monarch is anointed with the oil of Clovis and girt with the sword of Charlemagne.
events.html: • 1515 – Coronation of Francis I of France takes place at Reims Cathedral, where the new monarch is anointed with the oil of Clovis and girt with the sword of Charlemagne.[7]

events.description: Henry VIII of England secretly marries his second wife Anne Boleyn.
events.html: • 1533 – Henry VIII of England secretly marries his second wife Anne Boleyn.[8]

events.description: São Paulo, Brazil, is founded by Jesuit priests.
events.html: • 1554 – São Paulo, Brazil, is founded by Jesuit priests.[9]

events.description: Battle of Mikatagahara: In Japan, Takeda Shingen defeats Tokugawa Ieyasu.
events.html: • 1573 – Battle of Mikatagahara: In Japan, Takeda Shingen defeats Tokugawa Ieyasu.[10]

events.description: Luanda, the capital of Angola, is founded by the Portuguese navigator Paulo Dias de Novais.
events.html: • 1576 – Luanda, the capital of Angola, is founded by the Portuguese navigator Paulo Dias de Novais.

events.description: Walter Raleigh is knighted, shortly after renaming North America region "Virginia", in honor of Elizabeth I, Queen of England, sometimes referred to as the "Virgin Queen".
events.html: • 1585 – Walter Raleigh is knighted, shortly after renaming North America region "Virginia", in honor of Elizabeth I, Queen of England, sometimes referred to as the "Virgin Queen".[11]

events.description: The Battle of Ayubale results in the destruction of most of the Spanish missions in Florida.
events.html: • 1704 – The Battle of Ayubale results in the destruction of most of the Spanish missions in Florida.

events.description: Moscow University is established on Tatiana Day.
events.html: • 1755 – Moscow University is established on Tatiana Day.

events.description: Port Egmont, the first British settlement in the Falkland Islands near the southern tip of South America, is founded.
events.html: • 1765 – Port Egmont, the first British settlement in the Falkland Islands near the southern tip of South America, is founded.

events.description: Shays' Rebellion: The rebellion's largest confrontation, outside the Springfield Armory, results in the killing of four rebels and the wounding of twenty.
events.html: • 1787 – Shays' Rebellion: The rebellion's largest confrontation, outside the Springfield Armory, results in the killing of four rebels and the wounding of twenty.

events.description: The British Parliament passes the Constitutional Act of 1791 and splits the old Province of Quebec into Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
events.html: • 1791 – The British Parliament passes the Constitutional Act of 1791 and splits the old Province of Quebec into Upper Canada and Lower Canada.

events.description: The London Corresponding Society is founded.
events.html: • 1792 – The London Corresponding Society is founded.

events.description: University of Virginia chartered by Commonwealth of Virginia, with Thomas Jefferson one of its founders.
events.html: • 1819 – University of Virginia chartered by Commonwealth of Virginia, with Thomas Jefferson one of its founders.[12]

events.description: The Wedding March by Felix Mendelssohn is played at the marriage of Queen Victoria's daughter, Victoria, and Friedrich of Prussia, and becomes a popular wedding processional.
events.html: • 1858 – The Wedding March by Felix Mendelssohn is played at the marriage of Queen Victoria's daughter, Victoria, and Friedrich of Prussia, and becomes a popular wedding processional.

events.description: The Bulgarian National Bank is founded.
events.html: • 1879 – The Bulgarian National Bank is founded.

events.description: Thomas Edison and Alexander Graham Bell form the Oriental Telephone Company.
events.html: • 1881 – Thomas Edison and Alexander Graham Bell form the Oriental Telephone Company.

events.description: Nellie Bly completes her round-the-world journey in 72 days.
events.html: • 1890 – Nellie Bly completes her round-the-world journey in 72 days.

events.description: Richard Strauss's opera Elektra receives its debut performance at the Dresden State Opera.
events.html: • 1909 – Richard Strauss's opera Elektra receives its debut performance at the Dresden State Opera.

events.description: Alexander Graham Bell inaugurates U.S. transcontinental telephone service, speaking from New York to Thomas Watson in San Francisco.
events.html: • 1915 – Alexander Graham Bell inaugurates U.S. transcontinental telephone service, speaking from New York to Thomas Watson in San Francisco.

events.description: Sinking of the SS Laurentic after hitting two German mines off the coast of northwest Ireland.
events.html: • 1917 – Sinking of the SS Laurentic after hitting two German mines off the coast of northwest Ireland.[13]

events.description: The Ukrainian People's Republic declares independence from Soviet Russia.
events.html: • 1918 – The Ukrainian People's Republic declares independence from Soviet Russia.

events.description: The Finnish Defence Forces (The White Guards) are established as the official army of independent Finland, and Baron C. G. E. Mannerheim is appointed its Commander-in-Chief.
events.html: • 1918 – The Finnish Defence Forces (The White Guards) are established as the official army of independent Finland, and Baron C. G. E. Mannerheim is appointed its Commander-in-Chief.[14]

events.description: The 1924 Winter Olympics opens in Chamonix, in the French Alps, inaugurating the Winter Olympic Games.
events.html: • 1924 – The 1924 Winter Olympics opens in Chamonix, in the French Alps, inaugurating the Winter Olympic Games.

events.description: Second Sino-Japanese War: The Chinese National Revolutionary Army begins the defense of Harbin.
events.html: • 1932 – Second Sino-Japanese War: The Chinese National Revolutionary Army begins the defense of Harbin.

events.description: The Guiding Light debuts on NBC radio from Chicago. In 1952 it moves to CBS television, where it remains until September 18, 2009.
events.html: • 1937 – The Guiding Light debuts on NBC radio from Chicago. In 1952 it moves to CBS television, where it remains until September 18, 2009.

events.description: Pope Pius XII elevates the Apostolic Vicariate of the Hawaiian Islands to the dignity of a diocese. It becomes the Roman Catholic Diocese of Honolulu.
events.html: • 1941 – Pope Pius XII elevates the Apostolic Vicariate of the Hawaiian Islands to the dignity of a diocese. It becomes the Roman Catholic Diocese of Honolulu.

entities.name: Apostolic Vicariate of the Hawaiian Islands

events.description: World War II: Thailand declares war on the United States and United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Thailand declares war on the United States and United Kingdom.

events.description: World War II: The Battle of the Bulge ends.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Battle of the Bulge ends.

events.description: The United Mine Workers rejoins the American Federation of Labor.
events.html: • 1946 – The United Mine Workers rejoins the American Federation of Labor.

events.description: United Nations Security Council Resolution 1 relating to Military Staff Committee is adopted.
events.html: • 1946 – United Nations Security Council Resolution 1 relating to Military Staff Committee is adopted.

events.description: Thomas Goldsmith Jr. files a patent for a "Cathode Ray Tube Amusement Device", the first ever electronic game.
events.html: • 1947 – Thomas Goldsmith Jr. files a patent for a "Cathode Ray Tube Amusement Device", the first ever electronic game.[15]

events.description: The first Emmy Awards are presented in the United States; the venue is the Hollywood Athletic Club.
events.html: • 1949 – The first Emmy Awards are presented in the United States; the venue is the Hollywood Athletic Club.

events.description: The National Association of Broadcasters in the United States reacts to the "payola" scandal by threatening fines for any disc jockeys who accept money for playing particular records.
events.html: • 1960 – The National Association of Broadcasters in the United States reacts to the "payola" scandal by threatening fines for any disc jockeys who accept money for playing particular records.

events.description: In Washington, D.C., US President John F. Kennedy delivers the first live presidential television news conference.
events.html: • 1961 – In Washington, D.C., US President John F. Kennedy delivers the first live presidential television news conference.

events.description: Blue Ribbon Sports, which would later become Nike, is founded by University of Oregon track and field athletes.
events.html: • 1964 – Blue Ribbon Sports, which would later become Nike, is founded by University of Oregon track and field athletes.

events.description: South Vietnamese junta leader and Prime Minister Nguyen Cao Ky fires rival, Deputy Prime Minister and Defence Minister Nguyen Huu Co, while the latter is overseas on a diplomatic visit.
events.html: • 1967 – South Vietnamese junta leader and Prime Minister Nguyen Cao Ky fires rival, Deputy Prime Minister and Defence Minister Nguyen Huu Co, while the latter is overseas on a diplomatic visit.[16]

events.description: Brazilian Army captain Carlos Lamarca deserts in order to fight against the military dictatorship, taking with him ten machine guns and 63 rifles.
events.html: • 1969 – Brazilian Army captain Carlos Lamarca deserts in order to fight against the military dictatorship, taking with him ten machine guns and 63 rifles.

events.description: Charles Manson and four "Family" members (three of them female) are found guilty of the 1969 Tate–LaBianca murders.
events.html: • 1971 – Charles Manson and four "Family" members (three of them female) are found guilty of the 1969 Tate–LaBianca murders.

events.description: Idi Amin leads a coup deposing Milton Obote and becomes Uganda's president.
events.html: • 1971 – Idi Amin leads a coup deposing Milton Obote and becomes Uganda's president.

events.description: Pope John Paul II starts his first official papal visits outside Italy to The Bahamas, Dominican Republic, and Mexico.
events.html: • 1979 – Pope John Paul II starts his first official papal visits outside Italy to The Bahamas, Dominican Republic, and Mexico.

events.description: Mother Teresa is honored with India's highest civilian award, the Bharat Ratna.
events.html: • 1980 – Mother Teresa is honored with India's highest civilian award, the Bharat Ratna.

events.description: The National Resistance Movement topples the government of Tito Okello in Uganda.
events.html: • 1986 – The National Resistance Movement topples the government of Tito Okello in Uganda.

events.description: Avianca Flight 052 crashes in Cove Neck, New York, killing 73.
events.html: • 1990 – Avianca Flight 052 crashes in Cove Neck, New York, killing 73.[17]

events.description: Five people are shot outside the CIA Headquarters in Langley, Virginia. Two are killed and three wounded.
events.html: • 1993 – Five people are shot outside the CIA Headquarters in Langley, Virginia. Two are killed and three wounded.

events.description: The spacecraft Clementine by BMDO and NASA is launched.
events.html: • 1994 – The spacecraft Clementine by BMDO and NASA is launched.

events.description: The Norwegian rocket incident: Russia almost launches a nuclear attack after it mistakes Black Brant XII, a Norwegian research rocket, for a US Trident missile.
events.html: • 1995 – The Norwegian rocket incident: Russia almost launches a nuclear attack after it mistakes Black Brant XII, a Norwegian research rocket, for a US Trident missile.

events.description: Billy Bailey becomes the last person to be hanged in the United States.
events.html: • 1996 – Billy Bailey becomes the last person to be hanged in the United States.

events.description: During a historic visit to Cuba, Pope John Paul II demands political reforms and the release of political prisoners while condemning US attempts to isolate the country.
events.html: • 1998 – During a historic visit to Cuba, Pope John Paul II demands political reforms and the release of political prisoners while condemning US attempts to isolate the country.

events.description: A suicide attack by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam on Sri Lanka's Temple of the Tooth kills eight and injures 25 others.
events.html: • 1998 – A suicide attack by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam on Sri Lanka's Temple of the Tooth kills eight and injures 25 others.

events.description: A 6.0 magnitude earthquake hits western Colombia killing at least 1,000.
events.html: • 1999 – A 6.0 magnitude earthquake hits western Colombia killing at least 1,000.

events.description: Invasion of Iraq: A group of people leave London, England, for Baghdad, Iraq, to serve as human shields, intending to prevent the U.S.-led coalition troops from bombing certain locations.
events.html: • 2003 – Invasion of Iraq: A group of people leave London, England, for Baghdad, Iraq, to serve as human shields, intending to prevent the U.S.-led coalition troops from bombing certain locations.

events.description: A stampede at the Mandhradevi temple in Maharashtra, India kills at least 258.
events.html: • 2005 – A stampede at the Mandhradevi temple in Maharashtra, India kills at least 258.

events.description: Mexican professional wrestler Juana Barraza is arrested in connection with the serial killing of at least ten elderly women.
events.html: • 2006 – Mexican professional wrestler Juana Barraza is arrested in connection with the serial killing of at least ten elderly women.

events.description: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 409 crashes into the Mediterranean Sea off the coast of Na'ameh, Lebanon, killing 90.
events.html: • 2010 – Ethiopian Airlines Flight 409 crashes into the Mediterranean Sea off the coast of Na'ameh, Lebanon, killing 90.[18]

events.description: The first wave of the Egyptian revolution begins throughout the country, marked by street demonstrations, rallies, acts of civil disobedience, riots, labour strikes, and violent clashes.
events.html: • 2011 – The first wave of the Egyptian revolution begins throughout the country, marked by street demonstrations, rallies, acts of civil disobedience, riots, labour strikes, and violent clashes.

entities.name: Timeline of the Egyptian Revolution of 2011

events.html: • 2013 – At least 50 people are killed and 120 people are injured in a prison riot in Barquisimeto, Venezuela.
